 	<h2> Got an Email to Reply? STOP!</h2>
 	<img class= "img-responsive"src = "https://s3.amazonaws.com/prabal-assets/emailreply.jpg" alt ="Email Reply" style="padding-top:20px">
 	<p style="padding-top:20px">	
 		Most of the us receive emails from one to many everyday at work. Some of us take no time in replying back those emails the moment we receive it. It is usually all good until one day when we realize one of these situations have occurred-"Shit, I missed the attachment", "Oh well,I forgot to include one more point", " Wait, was I supposed to even reply?" etc. I am sure we all have gone through these at some point of time.<p> 
		<p>We may sometimes come as a belligerent person the way we reply an email. Much of it depends on the time spent on the email before sending it out. Usually, time taken on replying back an email can come as more concise and apt. In short, the more is the better.</p>
		<p>On the other side, we may restlessly wait for an email back from our boss or co-worker.It can get frustrating too at certain times when we realize how important the email is and think that our boss or co-worker does not feel the same way. Lets all accept it, most of us read all the emails we receive, even bosses do but what makes it different is who replies them back early. It takes a different level of mindset, understanding and sometimes psyche of the person to whom one is replying to. While some of us may find it extremely ill mannered not to receive an email reply back after we have sent it which unfortunately the receiver does not think the same way.</p>
		<p>Senior or successful people in the job as we might all have faced, they do not seem to reply back to our emails as early as we might anticipate. There is a reason for that. Reasons are fairly simple though.</p>
		<h4>Here are 11 reasons why it is a good choice to follow their path and wait until we should reply back to an email:- </h4>
		<p style="padding-top:20px">1. They do not like to reply important emails towards the end of the day as they think important decisions need to be taken in the morning when the mind is fresh(So you might have to wait till next day when your boss gets into office if you have sent an email asking for reply on some important decision towards the end of the day).</p>
		<p>2. They understand that effective communication is the key to any successful business. Effective does not necessarily mean quicker response but a reply as if it concludes the conversation.<p>
		<p>3. They do not push it too hard in emails, they give a call back instead. <p>
		<p>4. They do not want to send out an email in hurry to be apologetic in the next email.<p>
		<p>5. They like to understand the entire situation before anything they may want to reply back.<p>
		<p>6. They like to connect the dots(from previous conversations) and also anticipate future
		replies that you may do.<p>
		<p>7. They do not want to make any mistakes knowingly or unknowingly in their replies.<p>
		<p>8. They think an email with appropriate information is better than an insufficient faster email.<p>
		<p>9. They do not get provoked easily by emails.<p>
		<p>10. They mark emails from certain people as unread and like to reply back them when they are at ease.<p>
		<p>11. They usually read the subject and decide when to reply.(Make sure your subject is appealing enough if its an important email to go unnoticed).<p>
		Bottom line is to not reply an email the moment you receive it until its an emergency situation. Take your time to understand the situation, background and spend some extra few seconds/minutes/hours to provide all the necessary information in one single email. Nobody likes to email back and forth regarding the same thing. Next time you receive an email, do not hurry yourself to reply back immediately. An incomplete quick email reply is far annoying than a late well composed email.
		Nevertheless, our email replies speak a lot about us as a person.

 	</p>
